In the battle of life a man must, if need be, slay any natural affection, or cut away his own membem, rather than fail, holding all things subservient to the interests of war ; but there is no hint in this teaching that all rnen will fight the better for being loveless or halt or blind, that those provinces of activity which may be misused should be abolished. From the life of Jesus it is evident that the case must be personal and extreme when the temptation ought to be cut off with the sin. Rather is the Christian's common way that narrowest path that lies along the height between the bottoni— less slopes of disuse and abuse.
